In 1959, Vargas Llosa enthusiastically supported Fidel Castroâs socialist revolution in Cuba. At one point, he even housed Che Guevaraâs mother in his apartment. But as Castroâs regime developed, Vargas Llosa grew uneasy. During a trip to Havana, he learned that gay Cubans were being imprisoned with counterrevolutionaries and common criminals in forced-labor camps. âSome of them had that totally idealistic idea that the revolution was not only going to bring socialism, but it was also going to change customs, that there would be a homosexual liberation,â he said. He told me he sent a private letter to Castro, expressing his confusion and surprise.
